{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523945"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:00:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:00:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13939"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13939"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.15,0.62,0.12,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48715"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6565"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13939"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33665"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"735"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13245"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48715"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic 10 days after sustaining a right shoulder dislocation during a football game. The dislocation was reduced in the Emergency Department within hours of the injury. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He has sensory impairment over the lateral aspect of the forearm from just below the elbow to just above the wrist and weakness of elbow flexion. The biceps deep tendon reflex is decreased. The rest of his examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely affected based on the clinical findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Median nerve","Axillary nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with an injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. This nerve supplies motor function to the biceps brachii and brachialis muscles (responsible for elbow flexion) and sensory innervation to the lateral forearm. The depressed biceps reflex further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury typically presents with sensory loss over the lateral aspect of the upper arm (not the forearm) and weakness in shoulder abduction. While it is a common complication of shoulder dislocation, it doesn\u0027t match the symptoms described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects sensation in the palmar aspect of the thumb, index, and middle fingers, and the radial half of the ring finger. It doesn\u0027t typically cause weakness in elbow flexion or sensory changes in the lateral forearm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury would typically present with wrist drop and sensory loss over the posterior forearm and the dorsum of the hand, which is not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury typically affects the medial aspect of the hand and forearm, not the lateral aspect as described here. It also doesn\u0027t cause weakness in elbow flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while axillary nerve injury is a common complication of shoulder dislocation, other brachial plexus elements can also be affected, as seen in this case with the musculocutaneous nerve involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Axillary nerve injury is a common complication of shoulder dislocation, presenting with sensory loss over the lateral upper arm and weakness of shoulder abduction.","Musculocutaneous nerve injury can occur with shoulder dislocation, causing weakness of elbow flexion and sensory loss over the lateral forearm."],"references":["Liveson JA. Nerve lesions associated with shoulder dislocation; an electrodiagnostic study of 11 cases. J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry. 1984 Jul;47(7):742-4. doi: 10.1136/jnnp.47.7.742. PMID: 6747652; PMCID: PMC1027907.","Knipe H, Hacking C, Robertson S, et al. Musculocutaneous nerve. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 16 Jul 2024) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-24693"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33665"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13939"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33665"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-16T12:06:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T13:23:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6565"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48715"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.